{{Languages of | country = Bulgaria | official = [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] | minority = [[Turkish language|Turkish]], [[Romani language|Romani]] | foreign = [[Russian language|Russian]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Italian language|Italian]] |sign=[[Bulgarian Sign Language]] }} The [[official language]] of [[Bulgaria]] is [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]. According to the 2001 census, 84.5% of the country's population speak Bulgarian natively.<ref name="nsi.bg">{{cite web|url = http://www.nsi.bg/Census/MotherTongue.htm|title = НАСЕЛЕНИЕ КЪМ 01.03.2001 Г. ПО ОБЛАСТИ И МАЙЧИН ЕЗИК (Inhabitants as at 01.03.2001 by province and mother tongue)|publisher=NSI|date=1 March 2001}}</ref>
== 2001 Census == The 2001 census defines an ethnic group as a "community of people, related to each other by origin and language, and close to each other by mode of life and culture"; and one's mother tongue as "the language a person speaks best and usually uses for communication in the family (household)".<ref name="culturalpolicies.net">{{cite web|author=Cultrual Policies and Trends in Europe|title=Population by ethnic group and mother tongue, 2001|url=http://www.culturalpolicies.net/web/bulgaria.php?aid=421|accessdate=2 December 2008}}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" style="width:100%;" |- ! Native Language !! By ethnic group !! Percentage !! By first language !! Percentage |- |[[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] || 6,655,210 || 83.93% ||6,997,000 || 88.46% |- |[[Turkish language|Turkish]] || 746,660 || 9.42% ||663,000 || 8.62% |- |[[Roma language|Romani]] || 370,910 || 4.67% || 128,000|| 1.13% |- |Others || 69,000|| 0.87% || 71,000 || 0.89% |- |Total|| 7,928,900|| 100% || 7,928,900 || 100% <ref name="culturalpolicies.net"/> |}
== Bulgarian == {{main|Bulgarian language}} Bulgarian is the country's only official language. It's spoken by the vast majority of the Bulgarian population and used at all levels of society. It is a European language, a member of the Slavic linguistic group. Its closest relative is the [[Macedonian language]] and the difference between the two are on dialectal level.
Bulgarian is written with [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]], which also has been exported to other languages, notably [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Serbian language|Serbian]].
== Minority languages == '''Turkish''' {{main|Turks in Bulgaria}} The [[Turks in Bulgaria|Turks]] constitute the largest minority group in the country. The Turks in Bulgaria are descendants of [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] settlers who came from [[Anatolia]] across the narrows of the [[Dardanelles]] and the [[Bosporus]] following the Ottoman conquest of the Balkans in the late 14th and early 15th centuries, as well as Bulgarian converts to Islam who became Turkified during the centuries of Ottoman rule.<ref>Stein, Jonathan. ''The Politics of National Minority Participation in Post-communist Europe'', p. 238. M.E. Sharpe, 2000. {{ISBN|0-7656-0528-7}}</ref><ref>R.J.Crampton. "A concise history of Bulgaria", p. 36. Cambridge University Press, 1997.</ref>
'''Roma''' {{main|Romani people in Bulgaria}} The [[Romani people in Bulgaria|Romani]] constitute the second largest minority group in the country. The Romani in Bulgaria are descendants of [[Romani people|Romani]] nomadic migrants who came from [[India]] across the narrows of the [[Dardanelles]] and the [[Bosporus]], in the late 13th century<ref name="tomova">Tomova, ''Ethnic Dimensions of poverty in Bulgaria'', p. 15</ref> and following the Ottoman conquest of the Balkans in the late 14th and early 15th centuries, and also during the five centuries of Ottoman occupation.<ref name="tomova"/><ref>Marushiakova et al., ''Gypsies in the Ottoman Empire: a contribution to the history of the Balkans'', p. 26</ref>
Other minority languages spoken are [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]], [[Tatar language|Tatar]], [[Greek language|Greek]], [[Romanian language|Romanian]], [[Aromanian language|Aromanian]] and [[Megleno-Romanian language|Megleno-Romanian]].
== Foreign languages == According to a Eurobarometer survey conducted in 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_386_en.pdf |format=PDF |title=SPECIAL EUROBAROMETER 386 Europeans and their Languages |publisher=ec.europa.eu |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106183351/http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_386_en.pdf |archivedate=2016-01-06 |df= }}</ref> [[English language|English]] was the most commonly known foreign language in Bulgaria (25% claimed workable knowledge of it), followed by [[Russian language|Russian]] (23%), and German (8%).
In the 2012 Eurobarometer survey,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_386_en.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-08-21 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106183351/http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_386_en.pdf |archivedate=2016-01-06 |df= }}</ref> however, the situation was different, with 25% of people saying they know [[English language|English]] well enough in order to be able to have a conversation, and only 23% answering [[Russian language|Russian]] (a decrease of 12 points). This is because many of the people who learned [[Russian language|Russian]] at school are from an older generation and some are now deceased or as time has elapsed, have forgotten how to speak the language. When asked which two languages, other than their mother tongue, would be the most useful for children to learn in their future, an overwhelming majority of respondents said [[English language|English]] (90%), with [[German language|German]] coming second (36%), and [[Russian language|Russian]] third (14%).<ref name="ec.europa.eu">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_386_en.pdf |title=Special Eurobarometer 386 - Europeans and their Languages |publisher=EC |date=June 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106183351/http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_386_en.pdf |archivedate=2016-01-06 |df= }}</ref>
