{{Expand German|date=February 2014}} {{Expand Dutch|date=February 2014}}
'''Petuh''' (Petu) is a [[mixed language]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uni-flensburg.de/fileadmin/databox/universitaet/dokumente/berichte/UFL_Forschungsbericht_2001-2003.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-07-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130712044713/http://www.uni-flensburg.de/fileadmin/databox/universitaet/dokumente/berichte/UFL_Forschungsbericht_2001-2003.pdf |archivedate=2013-07-12 |df= }}</ref> of [[Flensburg]], a mixture of [[German language|German]], [[Low German]], [[Danish language|Danish]], and [[Southern Jutish]] spoken in Flensburg on the German–Danish border. It is [[High German]] in vocabulary (with some Danish concepts and loan translations), but it has Danish and Low Saxon grammar and syntax.{{cn|date=February 2014}} It originated in the 19th century and was still vibrant in the 1950s, but it is now on the verge of extinction.
Petuh was named after partout card (Year pass) on the ferries on the [[Flensburg Fjord]]. It was known by the ''petuhtants'', mostly older women who met on the excursion boats and in the cafes along the fjord.
